In October 2019, there was a sewage back-up through the Laundry Room drain of the building I rent a basement appartment in (226 Broadway Avenue, Toronto, ON M4P 1V9) that flooded my unit and the common areas with sewage.Â 

Nahid Ghafouri (Landlord) did  not fully address the issue and I was forced to contact the Property Standards office.Â 

On December 12thÂ 2019, the City of Toronto Property Standards office inspected my unit.Â 

An order was delivered to Nahif Ghafouri (Landlord) noting the following infractions of the building code and that be repairs be completed by January 13thÂ 2020. (Folder #19 259594 PRS 00IV)

-Basement floor has dried sewage that came up from the drain and requires cleaning

-Sewage water backing up rom the floor drain and into common area and basement apartment

Since that time, Nahid Ghafouri did hire a plumber, but ingored the advice of what needed to be done, instead opting for a temp bandaid, but this did not resolve the issue.Â  As well, Nahid Ghafouri (Landlord) refused to clean the sewage and insisted I clean the sewage from the unit and common area and refrain from flushing toilet paper.Â 

In February 2020 Property Management By-Law Officer Bruce Quick referred the case to the Public Health department as the order had lapsed without the issue being resolved.Â 

In February 2020 the unit was inspected by Public Health Inspector Inessa Kirillova, where it was noted that the concerns were still present and posed a health hazard as it is sewage that is regularly backing up into the unit.Â 

On February 5th, 2020 Public Health delivered an order to Nahid Ghafouri (Landlord) asking them to hire professional contractors to remediate any structural conditions contributing to the sewage backup and to clean and disinfect all contaminated areas and surfaces.

To this date I have been forced to clean the sewage from my bathroom, floor and common area on a regular basis since this issue started in October 2019, a task that has grown impossible as the lack of plumbing worsens. 

 Nahid Ghafouri (landlord) has not responded to my requests for maintenance, and my request for information on the status of maintenance.Â 

The sewage backups happen almost daily causing my toilet, bathtub, and sink to be filled with hazardous sewage.Â 

This was an issue of great concern in January when the repairs were ordered to be completed by and is now of greater concern as we are in a pandemic, and these issues and biohazard have issued the apartment unliveable. Â Â

landlord_action_2: Landlord adamantly told us he was moving his family into the house and so we had to leave by the end of the summer. He also claimed he was doing renovations in order to prepare for moving in.  He never moved in.  He simply wanted us out so he could rent out the basement separately from the groundfloor/upper floor and make $800 more rent/month.  However, the house is too small to be split up and the basement is freezing in winter and the upstairs is roasting in the summer.   We never missed a rent payment deadline nor did we damage anything.  In Oct 2019, he placed an ad for new tenants in the ground floor/2nd level and also placed a separate ad to rent the basement .   He is clueless about being a good landlord in terms of property upkeep and understanding his obligations.
tenant_action: We moved out as unfortunately, based on studying previous similar cases, the law in practice is not in favor of the tenant because the landlord will simply lie and say he planned to move in but the plan changed due to some excuse.   The Landlord & Tenant Review Board as of middle 2019 did not have an issue with landlords using this loophole based on my research.  The amount of effort it takes to fight this loophole is not worth the fight unless you are single and can move  easily with short notice.

tenant_action: Parkdale Organize helped the Tenants by providing support in the creation of individual notice document. A significant number of tenants filled them out and signed them and we delivered them together on Aug 30 to the owners house at 16 Springhurst Ave. The landlords did not respond, however they did call police, who ultimately convinced Zhivago Marakathalingasivam to accept the documents and our group left the property. I spoke personally with Sgt. Vickers 14 Div. and he told me we were doing the right thing by organizing but when should keep the peace, or words to that effect. However since that time some of the tenants were provided with notices with police letterhead, I was not one of those. But all have now received a three page manifesto of abuse by the landlord's threatening action for participation in our ad hoc organization. I have not yet received notice of hearing and schedule of parties for this or my rental arrears which I also received with an above guide rental increase notice too boot.
location: 22 Springhurst Ave, Toronto, ON M6K 1A9, Canada

landlord_action_2:
Old landlord sold the home, and the new lndlord informed us that he plans to renovate, then move his immediate family in. This was clearly not true as a Google search revealed he is a realtor known for flipping houses, the home sale was a private sale, and he bought the house without ever having stepped foot inside and without an inspection. He only gave us verbal notice (not the corresponding eviction form - N12 I think it is?). When approached about the form, he sent us an N11 form (mutual agreement to end tenancy) which we refused to sign, stating that we want an N12. He refused us an N12, and we informed him of what he would have to pay us if we take him to the tenant board, which resulted in a cash settlement. 

There is a 2nd unit in the house, and although the tenants aren't moving out yet (another 2 months on their lease is left), they also have only been given verbal notice and have not received any formal eviction notices.
tenant_action:
My partner and myself informed the new landlord that since he failed to serve us the proper eviction notice, we would like a cash settlement in lieu of us bringing the gase to the Landlord and Tenant Board. 

We informed the other tenants in the house (duplex) about our situation. They have not received an eviction notice either and are also willing to state their rights to him in the hopes of receiving a cash settlement like we did.
location: 121 Langley Ave, Toronto, ON M4K 1B6, Canada

landlord_action_2: Consistent harassing phone calls from blocked numbers trying to illegally raise rent starting in mid july 2016 as well as threats to serve an N12  if I didnt pay her more cash under the table (She did file N12 October 2016 claiming she was moving in), unannounced visits demanding to get into unit, trying to give a range of 2 days of visits instead of scheduled times, served N12 and harassing threats to at least 3 other tenants, not doing requested maintenance, not doing essential repairs (there was a hole in the ceiling above shower for  6 months not being repaired and  mold growing), giving repairmen a key and they entered not at scheduled times. Eventually she served me an N12, i moved out Nov. 2016 because of her constant threats and harassment because she wanted more rent and I was paying under market value due to being there 6 years, she did not move in. she then also served notices of N12 of her moving in to at least 3 other tenants, some took cash settlements due to me signing an affidavit that she had already given one to me. She made numerous threats to call my work and accused me of trashing the place upon exit (untrue).  She gave a registered address only as a mailbox so that she couldnt be served papers.

landlord_action_2:
ATTN: Re: Threats, verbal and physical harassment, fraudulent N12. In mid April 2018 after the big ice storm we had a lot of serious leaks. The Kims (Jung Ja and her husband who built a large house behind 673 Spadina on Sussex Ave) refused to do anything/blamed the restaurant downstairs (Daddyoâ€™s Pasta who has been on a month to month lease for quite some time as the only lease they are offering Daddyo's to re-sign insists that they must take responsibility for the roofâ€¦ and they justly refuse). Jung Ja Kim and did not seem to care that there was water filling up the bowl shaped light fixtures and that light bulbs exploded! As we had also had no heat in my room/office for the last two winters, I decided to take matters in my own hands and file a complaint with the landlords tenants board. Upon inspection a gentleman from the tenants board said that yes, the place was hazardous but that serving the landlord usually results in tenant/landlord animosity, under the new laws I thought we would be reasonably invincible given that the notice seemed reasonable in that it was a request that they prove that they are taking action to fix matters within 30 days. On April 27th 2018 Jung Ja Kim received the notice from the tenants board (that explicitly detailed that it was OUR unit that called the tenants board) and went into Daddyo's waving it around with the word idiot sprawled across it - I believe her incorrect spelling was intentional. Shri (the sri lankan co-owner of Daddyo's) said he could not speak to her because he was on the phone with his wife regarding their son being hospitalized due to pneumonia. She proceed to get and dump a bag of rotten compost all over the restaurant floor and HIT SHRI IN THE FACE AND MADE HIM BLEED. Shri took the physical abuse (she did draw blood on his face, I saw it) and did not want to call the police because in his words "he is a brown guy and she is an old Korean woman, who will they believe?" but I insisted on calling the police. Upon arrival they told me she has a history of violence and went to her house to investigate and she called the police on the police because she did not believe they were the real police, securing the restaurant with a restraining order against her. Daddyo's was closed for a week following the incident due to health restrictions and staff taking time off which I suppose because of the garbage dumping. The restaurant was given a 6 month eviction notice - but it looks like they are still there. Since the incident she came into our place multiple times unannounced, and shoved my then-partner at that time aside to enter. It gets worseâ€¦ On May 3rd she sent an eviction notice with the address spelled wrong (it said 47 Sussex which is a property she used to own where she built their new residence I believe?), It also spelled my partners last name wrong, her OWN name wrong (it says Mrs. Kin!) and said the reason for eviction is that she is leaving Mr. Kim due to â€œmarital separationâ€, After she started banging pots and pans at 2am behind our kitchen and HIT ME IN THE HEAD WITH A CANOE PADDLE (I have a audio of this incident!!!) calling me STUPID SHORT GIRL, TOOK OUR MAILBOX AWAY, we could no longer live in peace there and decided to leave, so I sent her lawyer an email saying we would go peacefully if she she filed an L2 found on to enable her to send us an N11. Her lawyer avaturi@vclawyers.ca
wrote back on June 14 2018 â€œFurther to your correspondence, Iâ€™ve had an opportunity to discuss the file with your landlord. She is of the position that she rather not have to go through with the expenses and resources needed for an application and hearing process. Sheâ€™d rather allow you to stay as tenants. That being the case, please note that there will be no credit applied to your rent, and as such you will still need to make your June and July rent payment as usual.â€ Obviously it was too chaotic a situation to stay in so we moved out and filed a notice with the tenants board so that they could check if she was occupying the place after her departure. I would pass 673 Spadina for the year + following on my commute home from work - the lights were DARK (and the neighbours who I kept in touch with via email verified she NEVER lived there but put on a big show knocking on their door to say â€œI LIVE HERE NOWâ€) until December 31st 2019 when new tenants arrived. Three young music students from Europe I believe. I talked to them to warn them on this day when I saw the lights onâ€¦. Then life went on.

landlord_action_2:
The new landlord left a memo in the mailboxes of all the tenants after they purchased the building (20/04/30) stating that they would be picking up rental cheques at the beginning of the month if we left them in the mailboxes. We left the cheques in the mailbox and they were initially picked up every month but not deposited. They were deposited all at once about 6 months in. Then the landlord stopped picking up cheques all together after they gave the N13 notice (around the end of April). 

Yesterday, (21/07/21) two men that I did not recognize came into the apartment and were knocking on doors. I spoke to them without letting them into the apartment and they initially stated that they worked with the landlord, and then that they were the landlord. They also said that they were there to "inspect the units" and see who was still living there. One man said that we were supposed to be out of the building by the end of the month prior (June), but we corrected him saying that the N13 said by the end of July. The man who was speaking then tried to enter our downstairs neighbour's apartment with the keys he had. We told him he wasn't allowed to just enter because no notice had been given. The other man, who we later learned was Jonathan West -  appointed by the Landlord for asset protection/acquisition - said that he had left notice in the mailboxes. I'd been home the entire week before, checking the mailbox regularly and there was no notice left. When I asked why he was lying about it he backed off and stopped entering the apartment. He complained he had no way to contact us so we told him to leave his information in the mailboxes. He walked away and didn't leave the information.

landlord_action_2:
In mid-March I was left homeless by a fire in another unit. Toronto Hydro couldn't isolate the wiring to the affected unit because nothing was labelled properly, so they cut electricity to the whole house. The landlords kept it off to make it impossible for the four tenants to return to our units. Over the next couple of months they sent us three letters saying our tenancies were terminated immediately. They never served N13s. They restored electricity to the house, but not to any of our units. They continued building a new apartment in the basement while telling us that the fire had left the entire house unliveable. Even after I filed an application with the LTB, they violated an Interim Order by gutting all 4 apartments to convert the house into a single-family home. They adjourned my hearing twice, once with "technical issues" and once by feigning illness. One day I was taking photos and videos of my unit for evidence, and the husband entered and assaulted me. On my last visit to the house he barricaded the door, denying me access to my unit. I could go on. 
To the landlords, the fire was nothing but a great opportunity to finally kick out long-term tenants. This had been my home for 16 years and I was paying $700/month. I was a good tenant to these people for 13 years, and they left me homeless and put me through hell for more than eight months.
tenant_action: I took the landlords to the LTB, where they agreed to a settlement of $35,000, the maximum settlement.

landlord_action_2:
-verbal discussion of plans for the building on same date as possession changed hands
-multiple N13s served upon all tenants (all have been long standing tenants)
-1st N13s served along with N11s which offered $1000 to vacate prior to the termination date 
-another N13 served to all tenants with renovation plans changed because of denied building permits due to failure to apply for Rental Housing Demolition Permit etc. 
-tenant vacating due to lack of understanding of process asked to report on the activity of their neighbours and offered financial gain in return 
-renovation of empty units and common areas with no regard to mitigation of disruption to existing tenants, no notice or warning given. Noise level in excess of 110db recorded at times
-removal of and attempted removal of paid amenities after tenants exercised their rights 
-entry points unsecured multiple times to facilitate easy access for construction and demolition workers 
-no snow removal from driveway and parking spots unless Toronto bylaw was involved 
There has been much more however I feel that it is too much to list here and wouldnâ€™t be pertinent without the entire history.
tenant_action:
All remaining tenants have organized and presented a united front in order to fight for our homes. 
As Iâ€™m certain that our story isnâ€™t unique, it has dragged out for a long time which is definitely taking a toll on our wellbeing. There is so much more to our journey than I feel that I canâ€™t adequately express in this limited forum, however I feel it of utmost importance to, at very least, put our address on the radar through your site. Iâ€™m incredibly thankful that we have such resources available to us. 
We have retained a lawyer to help us in our pursuit and are currently, after almost a year and a half, still in what we once called our homes. It no longer feels like a home, but rather a place to go after our long days at work.
case_number: As there are other units involved in LTB filings, T2, T6, T5 etc, Iâ€™d prefer not to list the case number publicly. We are all still awaiting our hearing dates at this point in time.
